20 Sec. 29. 1. To declare a residential property to be a substandard property,
21 the district court must find:
22 (a) The residential property is maintained in a way that violates one or more
23 applicable habitability standards, housing codes or building codes, or any statute
24 or ordinance relating to habitability, building safety or fire safety;
25 (b) The condition of the residential property that is caused by the violation or
26 violations described in paragraph (a) is so extensive and of such a nature that the
27 health and safety of residents of the building or the public is substantially
28 endangered; and
29 (c) Any other factor that the district court finds relevant.
30 2. In determining whether to appoint a receiver for a substandard property,
31 the district court shall consider:
32 (a) Whether the owner of the substandard property has been afforded a
33 reasonable opportunity to repair or rehabilitate the property or otherwise abate
34 the condition; and
35 (b) Any other factor that the district court finds relevant.
36 3. The district court:
37 (a) Except as otherwise provided in paragraph (b), may appoint a nonprofit
38 organization, community development corporation or other person as a receiver.
39 (b) Shall not appoint any nonprofit organization, community development
40 corporation or person as a receiver unless the nonprofit organization, community
41 development corporation or person has demonstrated to the district court the
42 necessary capacity and expertise to develop and supervise a viable financial and
43 construction plan for the satisfactory rehabilitation of the substandard property.
44 4. An order issued by a district court declaring a residential property to be a
45 substandard property must, without limitation, set forth:
46 (a) The conditions found by the district court that make the residential
47 property a substandard property; and
48 (b) The repairs, rehabilitations and abatements that the district court finds to
49 be necessary in order to correct each violation of a habitability standard, housing
50 code or building code, or any statute or ordinance relating to habitability,
51 building safety or fire safety.
52 Sec. 30. 1. If the district court finds that there is a condition of the
