25 substandard property.
26 (c) Secure a cost estimate and construction plan from a licensed contractor
27 for the repairs, rehabilitation or abatement necessary to correct the conditions
28 cited in the order issued pursuant to section 29 of this act.
29 (d) Enter into contracts and employ a licensed contractor as necessary to
30 correct the conditions cited in the order issued pursuant to section 29 of this act.
31 (e) Collect all rents and income generated by the substandard property.
32 (f) Use all rents and income generated by the substandard property to pay for
33 the cost of the repairs, rehabilitation or abatement determined by the district
34 court to be necessary to correct the conditions cited in the order issued pursuant
35 to section 29 of this act.
36 (g) Borrow money to pay for repairs, rehabilitation or abatement necessary
37 to correct the conditions cited in the order issued pursuant to section 29 of this
38 act and to borrow money to pay for any relocation benefits for tenants that are
39 authorized pursuant to section 30 of this act and, with district court approval,
40 secure that debt and any money owed to the receiver for services performed
41 pursuant to this section with a lien on the residential property upon which the
42 substandard property is situated. The lien shall be recorded in the county
43 recorder’s office in the county wherein the substandard property is situated.
44 (h) To exercise any other power granted to a receiver pursuant to chapter 32
45 of NRS.
46 (i) Provide any relocation benefits to a tenant that are ordered by the court
47 pursuant to section 30 of this act.
48 3. If the district court appoints as a receiver a nonprofit organization or
49 community development corporation, in addition to the powers and duties that
50 are granted pursuant to subsection 2, the nonprofit organization or community
51 development corporation may apply for grants to assist in the rehabilitation of the
52 substandard property.

